<div class="column middle">
  <br><h1>All The President's Men</h1>
  <hr style='float: right; width:100%;'><br>
  
  <p>
  "How have you gone with getting in?"
  <br>
  "We haven't had any luck yet."
  <br>
  "Get some."
  </p>
  <p>
  All The Presidents Men follows two Washington Post reporters - Bob Woodwode and Carl Burnstein - as they investigate and report what we now know as the Watergate affair. What at first seems like a suspicious break in at a government facility, eventually escalates into a wide scale political conspiracy, of rigged elections, bribed officials, hushed up informants and stolen documents... And, it all actually happened.
  </p>
  <p>
  To uncover what occured required scores of interviews, telephone calls and good old investigative work. Even when legitimate information was uncovered, all sources refused to go on the record.
  </p>
  <p>
  Unfortunately, with so many names and shady accusations being thrown around, its fairly difficult to keep track of what's specifically going on, other than a vague direction of Bob and Carl getting closer to a story.
  </p>
  <p>
  The score is virtually non-existent, and is only used for brief tense moments... This is a pity. Something like music would have helped to move along the snail speed pace of the investigation. Acting is adequate, with the two main reporters providing just enough star power.
  </p>
  <p>
  Though a slow slog at times, All The President's Men was undeniably interesting purely by virture of its content. Furthermore, its style has set a strong precedent in investigative journalism movies; most notably, I think of Steven Spielberg's, The Post. If you're interested, give it a watch, but on the whole I'd say its probably not worth it.
  </p>
  <p>
  5.5/10
  </p>
  <br>
